definition.value: Antagonist of platelet surface glycoprotein-IIb/IIIa which has a key role in hemostasis and thrombosis such as platelet adhesion and aggregation.
A cyclic hydroxamic acid siderophore that is produced by several bacterial species and exhibits antitumour activity.
A hydroxycoumarin that is 4-hydroxycoumarin which is substituted at position 3 by a 1-phenylpropyl group.
A Fe(III)-complexed hydroxamate siderophore comprising equimolar amounts of iron(3+) and desferrioxamine B(3-)
An N-substituted diamine in which the diamine is cadaverine.
An EC 3.5.4.* (non-peptide cyclic amidine C-N hydrolase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of adenosine deaminase (EC 3.5.4.4).
A primary arylamine that is naphthalene substituted by an amino group at unspecified position.
A naphthylamine that is naphthalene substituted by an amino group at position 1.
A hydroxy fatty acid that consists of caprylic acid bearing two additional methyl substituents at positions 3 and 7 as well as a hydroxy substituent at position 6.
A branched-chain hydroxy fatty acid consisting of heptanoic acid with an isopropenyl group at the 3-position and the hydroxy group at the 6-position.
An acyclic desferrioxamine that is the N-acetyl derivative of desferrioxamine B.
A member of the class of diphenyl furans that is furan in which two of the hydrogens have been replaced by phenyl groups.
A member of the class of furans that is any diphenylfuran or their substituted derivatives.
A diphenylfuran in the the phenyl groups are located at positions 2 and 5 on the furan ring.
A diphenylfuran in the the phenyl groups are located at positions 2 and 4 on the furan ring.
A monoterpenoid that is oct-6-ene substituted by a hydroxy group at position 1 and methyl groups at positions 3 and 7.
The cis isomer of vaccenic acid.
A decenoic acid having its double bond in position 2.
A 2-decenoic acid having its double bond in the cis configuration.
A 2-decenoic acid having its double bond in the trans configuration. It is an intermediate metabolite in the fatty acid synthesis.
An EC 3.1.1.* (carboxylic ester hydrolase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of phospholipase A2 (EC 3.1.1.4).
A primary amine formally derived from ammonia by replacing one hydrogen atom by an aryl group. R-NH2 where R is an aryl group.
Any carboxylic ester where the carboxylic acid component is butyric acid.
A fatty acyl group derived from an icosenoic acid.
